":"1297","about 1335":"about 1335","1350":"1350","about 1350":"about 1350","1317":"1317","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Ryther, Yorkshire, England":"Ryther, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Southeby","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places called Southey, especially one in Culmstock (Devon), which is named with Middle English <i>bi south ey</i> ‘(place) to the south of the water’. Southey in Ecclesfield (Yorkshire) and Southey Green in Sible Hedingham (Essex) are from Middle English <i>south hey</i> ‘south enclosure’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":2,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Margaret Southeby was born about 1335, in Ryther, Yorkshire, England, her father, Sir William Southeby, was 37 and her mother, Lady Erline Roth, was 39. She had at least 1 son with Robert Ryther. She died in 1363, in Yorkshire, England, at the age of 29, and was buried in Ryther, Yorkshire, England."},"et":{"about 1335–1363":"umbes 1335–1363","1335–1363":"1335–1363","–1379":"–1379","1317–1363":"1317–1363","1350–1426":"1350–1426","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1297–Female":"1297–Surnud","1426":"1426","1337":"1337","1379":"1379","1335":"1335","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1363":"1363","1297":"1297","about 1335":"umbes 1335","1350":"1350","about 1350":"umbes 1350","1317":"1317","Y